article.description: Kevin Garnett had 25 points and 17 rebounds to lead Minnesota past the winless Miami Heat 88-79 Saturday night, the Timberwolves' second straight road win.
article.headline: Garnett has 25 points, 17 rebounds
article.linkText: Timberwolves turn off the Heat in Miami
article.story:
MIAMI (AP) -- Kevin Garnett made sure the Miami Heat's first win didn't come against the Minnesota Timberwolves. Garnett scored 25 points and had 16 rebounds to lead the Timberwolves to their second straight road victory, beating the winless Heat 88-79 Saturday night. Garnett, who also blocked five shots and added four assists, dominated on the inside, using his height advantage against the Heat's smaller front line as Minnesota followed up Friday's 100-71 rout of Orlando. The Heat are 0-6 for the first time since their inaugural season in 1988-89, when they opened 0-17. "Nobody wants to be the first victim," Garnett said. "We were fired up. We stressed the importance of taking care of ourselves in Miami. You have to keep the focus." Miami trailed by 19 points in the fourth quarter but made a late run to pull within 80-74 with just under two minutes to play. "We're going to lay it all out to win games," Heat forward Lamar Odom said. "We still have a lot of time to get going. We are not going to determine our season based on this slow start." Rookie Dwyane Wade, who finished with 19 points, made a pair of baskets to cut Minnesota's lead to six with 1:47 left. However, Fred Hoiberg nailed a 3-pointer to give the Timberwolves an 83-74 lead with 1:31 left, and Garnett blocked a shot by Caron Butler to seal the game. Butler returned to the lineup after missing the preseason and first five games of the regular season following surgery on his left knee. Butler, who has been limited to five practices, scored nine points in 31 minutes. Garnett made 10 of 19 shots in 36 minutes and controlled the action inside the paint, leading the Timberwolves both offensively and defensively. "Kevin was extremely good defensively," Minnesota coach Flip Saunders said. "He had a good game al around, the kind of game he usually has." Sam Cassell added 23 points, six assists and five rebounds, and Latrell Sprewell had 15 points for Minnesota. Eddie Jones had 21 points to lead the Heat, who are 0-6 for the first time since opening their inaugural season in 1988-89 with 17 straight losses. The Timberwolves took control of the game in the third quarter, erasing a 41-40 halftime deficit by outscoring Miami 28-16. Garnett and Sprewell combined for 19 points in the period. Sprewell hit a pair of 3-pointers, the second of which put Minnesota ahead 58-48 with 5:19 left. Garnett had no problem getting his jump shot off against the smaller Heat and made four of five shots in the period, including a short jumper that opened a 14-point lead in the closing seconds. "I was feeling a little better in the third, and I was able to knock down some 3s that gave us a little bit of cushion," said Sprewell, who has been nursing a sore Achilles' tendon. Gary Trent's short jumper put the Timberwolves up 74-59 with 9:07 left in the game. Miami pulled within 78-67 on Jones' 3-pointer with 4:19 left. "It's going to take a lot more than what we're giving to become a good team and win games," Jones said. "This is something we can turn around, but we need to focus a little harder."

Game notes
Tyrone Hill played his first game with the Heat. Hill, who signed with the team on Friday, played just two minutes and was scoreless. ... Garnett has led the Timberwolves in scoring in five of seven games. ... Wade returned to the starting lineup after missing two games with a left hip pointer.
